The existing tests cover level gates and tier boundaries, but "unlock state persistence" (monotonicity — higher levels never drop previously-unlocked items) is missing. I'll add a dedicated describe block for it.

`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
**Why monotonicity matters as a separate test concern**: A naive implementation could re-filter from config each call and accidentally drop entries if the config is mutated or the predicate flips. Monotonicity tests catch this without mocking — they just call the function twice with different levels and assert superset containment using `expect.arrayContaining()`.
`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`
